{[%evp 0,79,17,26,26,-16,37,11,22,17,5,17,28,17,17,7,52,43,58,43,38,-10,-4,-3,
36,1,29,16,24,16,20,20,20,20,44,21,45,30,54,52,48,44,78,43,27,34,69,69,66,66,
139,121,132,99,122,119,268,247,199,199,186,227,227,219,188,160,296,325,313,228,
319,346,393,393,393,414,618,626,634,681,710,683]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7
4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O a6 8. d5 {Undoubtedly, this is one of
the most ambitious continuations. This advance can be employed in various
situations but White often waits for a7-a6 and only then pushes his d-pawn.}
Na5 {A double-edged move: Black gains a tempo by attacking the c4-pawn, but
the knight is clearly misplaced and in some cases might even be trapped. On
the other hand, any other retreat would be a concession - White's space
advantage definitely starts to tell.} 9. b3 ({The Classical Yugoslav starts
with} 9. Nd2 c5 10. Qc2 Rb8 11. b3 b5 {and usually leads to a very complex and
tense play. This tabiya was very common 20-30 years ago, but nowadays it can
be rarely seen on the high level.}) 9... c5 {Like in the above-mentioned note,
Black plays c7-c5 in order to secure his poor Na5 and fix the c4-pawn, so
after b7-b5 Black could put strong pressure on it.} 10. dxc6 $5 {A very
interesting concept: White makes it possible for his opponent to liberate his
Na5, but it releases the pressure on the c4-pawn and heavily limits Black's
counter-attacking abilities on the queenside.} (10. Bb2 Rb8 11. Nd2 b5 12. Qc2
{takes us back to Classical Yugosalav paths.}) 10... Nxc6 {We reached an
important point. The current pawn structure is very common and can arise from
many theoretical lines, not just from the KID. Mostly, the character of the
play is quite comfortable for White who has control over the centre, and if he
manages to prevent Black from playing...b7-b5 or ..d6-d5 his knight could
enter d5 at the proper moment. This means that if Black is not able to develop
fast play on the queenside he will be doomed to passive defence. Moreover,
even if Black manages to play ...b7-b5 it often invites new trouble as it
would expose the c6-square, so after Nc3-d5 the exchange on d5 might
potentially be very dangerous for Black.} 11. Bb2 Rb8 12. Rc1 {This natural
move has a definite drawback as now the c1-square is not available for the
queen and the eventual Qd1-d2 invites Black to pin the knight with ..Qd8-a5.} (
{Therefore, somewhat stronger seems} 12. Qc1 $1 Qa5 ({After} 12... b5 13. cxb5
axb5 14. Nxb5 Rxb5 15. Qxc6 Rc5 16. Qa4 {Black does not have real compensation
for the pawn.}) 13. Rd1 Be6 14. Ng5 Bh6 ({Hardly better is} 14... Bg4 15. Nd5
Nxd5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Rxd5 Qc7 18. Qb2+ Kg8 19. c5 $36 {Flear,C - Lallemand,R
Chartres 2005}) 15. h4 Rbc8 16. Qe3 Ng4 17. Qf4 Nge5 {We have been following
the game Grandelius, N - Urkedal, F Chennai 2011 At this point White had no
reasons for rejecting the natural} 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. Rxd5 Qc7 20. Rad1 {, with
a superior position.}) 12... Bd7 13. Qd2 b5 $6 {Black is consistent in his
plans, but this is premature.} ({Much better was} 13... Qa5 14. Rfd1 ({After} 
14. Ba1 $6 Rfc8 15. Rfd1 b5 {Black took the upper hand in Danailov, S - Nowak,
I Poznan 1985}) 14... b5 15. Nd5 Qxd2 16. Nxd2 Nxd5 17. Bxg7 Nf4 $1 ({But not} 
17... Kxg7 $6 18. cxd5 Ne5 19. f4 Ng4 20. Rc7 $14) 18. Bxf8 Nxe2+ 19. Kf1 Nxc1
20. Bxe7 Nxe7 21. Rxc1 {White retains a slight positional advantage due to the
better pawn structure, but Black's position seems defensible.}) 14. Nd5 $1 {
That's the point! As usual, it is hard for Black to do with a powerful Nd5.}
Ne4 ({While} 14... Nxd5 $2 15. cxd5 Ne5 16. Nd4 Rc8 17. h3 {makes his position
practically lost in view of the weak c6-square.}) 15. Qc2 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 b4 ({
Black's position also seems very unpleasant after} 16... e6 17. Ne3 bxc4 18.
Nxc4 d5 19. Nce5 $36 {, but this was the lesser evil.}) 17. Ne1 {This
continuation was fully justified in the game,} ({but objectively stronger was} 
17. Nd2 $1 Nc5 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 $16) 17... Nc5 $6 {Rustam returns the
favor.} ({Black should have played} 17... f5 $1 18. Qc2 (18. Nd3 e6 19. Ne3 Qc7
{is not so clear either.}) 18... e6 19. Ne3 Nc3 $14 {due to the strong Nc3
Black's position remains playable.}) 18. Nd3 Nxd3 19. exd3 {Now after the
strong knight is gone it is much easier for White to increase the pressure.} e5
$2 {A decisive mistake.} ({It was necessary to play} 19... Ne5 20. Rfd1 e6 21.
Nf4 Nc6 22. d4 Ne7 $16) 20. f4 $1 {Boris correctly starts aggressive measures
on the kingside.} f6 21. Rf2 Nd4 22. Rcf1 Bf5 ({More stubborn was} 22... f5 {
but it would not change much:} 23. fxe5 dxe5 24. Re1 Re8 25. Rxe5 Rxe5 26. Qxd4
Re1+ 27. Rf1 Rxf1+ 28. Kxf1 $18) 23. Qd2 ({More energetic was} 23. g4 $1 Bxd3
24. fxe5 Bxf1 25. Nxf6+ Kg7 (25... Kh8 26. Qxd4 Bxg2 27. exd6 $18) 26. Qxd4
Bxg2 27. e6 Rxf6 28. g5 $18) 23... Kg7 24. Nxb4 Qb6 (24... Qa5 25. Nc6 Nxc6 26.
Bxc6 Qc5 27. Be4 $18) 25. Nd5 $18 {White is a pawn up in a better position.}
Qa7 26. Kh1 h5 27. Be4 h4 ({Black should have played} 27... Bh3 {, but after}
28. Bg2 Bf5 29. b4 {White would manage to create a passed pawn soon.}) 28. fxe5
hxg3 29. exf6+ Rxf6 30. Nxf6 gxf2 31. Nd5 Re8 32. Qe3 Qc5 33. Rxf2 a5 34. Rg2
Bxe4 35. dxe4 Nc6 36. Qg5 Ne5 37. Qf6+ Kh7 38. Rg3 Qc8 39. Qh4+ Kg7 40. Rh3 1-0

