{[%evp 0,81,26,26,26,-29,37,1,22,3,7,15,28,7,10,18,37,3,3,2,13,-6,61,20,17,1,1,
24,14,-33,30,24,39,4,70,66,79,79,76,165,181,203,169,190,187,182,182,182,204,
204,204,156,210,186,175,114,115,112,112,96,96,96,97,105,106,112,117,128,144,
156,164,112,134,123,131,131,152,109,123,130,128,127,131,89]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4
g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Bg5 Be6
10. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Yc3d5] A natural way of covering the c4-pawn. White's
knight is heading to e4 in order to increase the pressure along the h4-d8
diagonal. In addition, the long diagonal is now unlocked so White can consider
playing Nc3-d5 in the long run.} (10. Qc1 $5 {is a promising alternative, that
is covered in the files.}) 10... Qc8 {Teimour avoids the pin, but the Qc8
interrupts the connection between his rooks.} ({Another natural move was} 10...
h6 {, but the following game illustrates Black's issues:} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12.
Nde4 Be7 (12... Bg7 13. Nc5 $14) 13. Qc1 $1 {Attacking the Ph6 yields White an
important tempo for seizing the open file.} Kg7 14. Rd1 Qe8 15. Nd5 Rc8 16.
Nxe7 Qxe7 17. Nc3 $14 {Black got under long-lasting pressure in Vidit, S -
Onischuk,V Martuni 2016}) 11. Nd5 Nd7 {Black will have to do with a powerful
Nd5 for a while.} 12. b4 $1 {White continues expanding whilst preventing Black
from connecting his rooks.} h6 13. Be3 Re8 14. Rc1 Nd4 $2 {A dubious pawn
sacrifice.} ({The patient} 14... Ne7 {has to be prefered. In this case,
Black's position seems passive, but rather solid. For instance,} 15. Nb3 Nf5
16. Bd2 Nd4 17. Nxd4 ({Deserving of serious attention is} 17. b5 $5 c6 18. Re1
{, maintaining the tension.}) 17... exd4 18. e3 dxe3 19. Bxe3 Ne5 {Black
managed to equalize in Terbe, J - Belous, M Budapest 2019}) 15. Bxd4 exd4 16.
Nb3 {[%csl Rd4] The Pd4 will fall soon.} c5 $2 {Teimour is desperately trying
to activate his pieces, but this impulsive move leads to the collapse.} ({
Much better was} 16... Nf6 17. Nxd4 Bg4 18. h3 Bd7 $16 {the bishop pair leaves
Black with definite drawing chances.}) 17. bxc5 Nxc5 18. Nxd4 Bh3 19. Nb5 $1 {
[%csl Gb5,Gd5] White is just dominating over the board due to his powerful
knights.} Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Re5 (20... Qe6 21. Nbc7 Qe4+ 22. Kg1 $18) 21. f4 Re4
22. Nd6 Qe6 23. Nxe4 Qxe4+ 24. Rf3 $18 {White's material advantage is too big.}
Re8 25. Rc2 g5 26. h3 Ne6 27. Qd3 {Tamas decides to give up the lion's share
of his material advantage.} (27. e3 h5 28. Kh2 $18 {was simpler}) 27... Nd4 28.
Qxe4 Rxe4 29. Re3 Rxe3 30. Nxe3 gxf4 31. gxf4 Nxc2 32. Nxc2 {This endgame is
still absolutely lost for Black.} Kf8 33. Ne3 Ke8 34. Nf5 Bf8 35. e4 Kd7 36. e5
Kc6 37. Kf3 Kc5 38. Ke4 a5 (38... Kxc4 39. Nd6+ $18) 39. Kd3 a4 40. Kc3 b6 41.
Nd6 1-0

