1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O e5 8. dxe5
Nxe5 (8... dxe5 {is much more common, but after} 9. Bg5 {the nasty pin is a
cause of worries.}) 9. b3 $5 {White is satisfied with the current pawn
structure, so he deviates from capturing on e5.} Nxf3+ (9... c6 {can be well
met with} 10. Nd4 $5 {, maintaining the tension. For instance,} Re8 11. Bb2 h5
12. Qd2 h4 13. Rad1 hxg3 14. hxg3 $14 {Black did not have enough compensation
for the structural drawbacks in Krysa, L - Morales Rivera, J Badalona 2017})
10. Bxf3 Ne4 {[%csl Ya1] The most challenging as Black tries to make use of
the hanging Ra1.} ({In case of} 10... Bh3 {follows} 11. Re1 c6 12. Be3 Qa5 13.
Bd4 Rfe8 14. Qd2 Re6 15. Red1 $14) 11. Nxe4 $1 ({The timid} 11. Bxe4 Bxc3 12.
Rb1 Re8 {would not offer White much - the major exchanges clearly favour Black.
}) 11... Bxa1 12. Bg5 f6 13. Bh6 Be5 14. Bxf8 Qxf8 15. Bg2 {We have reached a
typical pawn structure in which the pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal can only
be neutralized by the weakening c7-c6 move. As the game shows, the Black's
bishop pair does not fully compensate for these issues.} f5 {Black can hardly
do without this advance - the Be5 can easily be trapped.} 16. Ng5 Qe7 17. Qd2
Bf6 $6 {The bishop retreat was unnecessary.} ({More precise was} 17... a5 18.
h4 Qf6 $14) 18. h4 $1 {Not only covering the Ng5, but also reminding Black of
his exposed king - potentially the h4-h5 advance might be dangerous.} a5 19. e4
$1 {The thematic break comes in time - Black's pieces are undeveloped, so once
the e-file opens, the Kg8 would come under attack.} h6 20. Nh3 fxe4 21. Nf4 $1
{This is much stronger} ({than} 21. Qxh6 Bf5 22. Ng5 Bxg5 23. hxg5 Qg7 $14)
21... Bf5 {This is forced, but now Black has to part with his bishop pair.} 22.
Nd5 Qg7 23. Nxf6+ Qxf6 24. Qd5+ {White regains the pawn in a favorable
situation.} Qf7 25. Qxb7 Re8 26. Re1 Kh7 $2 {A decisive mistake.} ({It was
necessary to get a rid of the weak a-pawn:} 26... a4 27. Re3 axb3 28. axb3 c5
$16) 27. Re3 $1 {White wins the pawn, and the game.} Rf8 ({Or} 27... Re5 28.
Bxe4 Qe7 29. Bxf5 Rxe3 30. fxe3 Qxe3+ 31. Kf1 Qc1+ 32. Kg2 Qd2+ 33. Kh3 gxf5
34. Qxc7+ Kg6 35. h5+ $18) 28. Qa7 $1 {Another nice prophylactic move.} a4 29.
Bxe4 axb3 30. axb3 Bg4 31. Re1 ({Even simpler was} 31. Qa2 $18) 31... Re8 32.
Qa5 Re5 33. Bd5 Rxe1+ 34. Qxe1 Qd7 35. Qe3 ({Good enough was} 35. f3 Bh3 36. g4
h5 37. gxh5 gxh5 38. Kf2 $18) 35... Bf5 36. b4 h5 37. b5 Kg7 38. Qd4+ Kh7 39.
Qf6 $1 {Black is almost paralyzed.} Qe8 40. Kh2 Qd7 41. Kg2 Qe8 42. Kf3 $1 {
It turns out that White's king can easily join the attack!} Kh6 43. Kf4 Bb1 44.
f3 Bc2 45. g4 hxg4 46. fxg4 Bd3 47. h5 Bb1 48. Be6 Bd3 49. g5+ Kxh5 50. Qg7 1-0

