{[%evp 0,71,25,32,32,-16,37,37,37,33,37,10,19,26,38,27,61,9,82,-18,32,8,-6,-10,
18,-37,-32,-59,-30,-69,-2,-2,39,18,18,38,38,55,91,91,125,123,154,95,147,154,
149,179,159,159,159,153,209,216,355,325,319,304,304,80,80,-2,127,127,134,118,
677,677,681,681,1982,2210,29991,29992]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4
O-O 5. g3 d6 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4 c6 9. h3 {This has always been
considered as White's main attempt to fight for the initiative in this line.}
Qb6 10. Re1 ({The most aggressive} 10. c5 $5 dxc5 11. dxe5 Ne8 12. e6 fxe6 13.
Ng5 {leads to very interesting play when White has full compensation for the
pawn, at the least.}) 10... exd4 11. Nxd4 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4,Rd6] This pawn
structure is statically bad for Black due to the lack of space and the weak
d6-pawn. But sometimes the active piece play might compensate for it. In this
particular case, the vulnerable Nd4 offers Black some counter-play.} Re8 12.
Re2 {A somewhat unusual manoeuvre which is aimed to secure the c4-pawn.} ({
Deserving of serious attention is also} 12. Nc2 $5 Nc5 ({After} 12... Ne5 13.
b3 Be6 14. Nd4 Nfd7 15. Be3 {Black was left in a very passive position in
Galyas, M - Amrein, R Balatonalmadi 2015}) 13. b4 Ncd7 14. Qxd6 Ne5 15. c5 Qa6
16. Bf4 Nh5 17. Bf1 Nc4 18. Qd3 Bxh3 19. Bxh3 Rad8 20. Nd5 {White was much
better, but eventually lost in Laznicka, V - Rapport, R Novy Bor 2014}) 12...
Qb4 ({The other common continuation -} 12... Ng4 {does not really change the
scenario:} 13. Rd2 Nge5 14. b3 Nc5 15. Rc2 a5 16. Be3 {White manages to fully
consolidate and maintain his merits.}) 13. Rc2 {[%csl Gb2,Gc4] That's the
point! White manages to cover the pawns on b2 and c4, so now the Bc1 can be
developed.} Nc5 14. Bd2 Qb6 15. Be3 a5 $6 {A careless move that makes it
possible for White to immediately exploit the pinned Nc5.} ({Better is} 15...
Qc7 16. f3 a5 17. Qd2 a4 {with a long strategic struggle, when White's chances
are slightly better.}) 16. Nb3 $1 {White changes the pawn structure in his
favour and acquires the pawn majority on the kingside. This factor weighs more
heavily than improving the weak d6-pawn.} a4 17. Nxc5 dxc5 18. Rac1 $1 {
An important prophylactic move that fully neutralizes any counter-play.} Be6
19. Rd2 a3 $2 {After this move Black's position is strategically lost.} ({
It was necessary to play} 19... Qb4 20. e5 Nd7 21. f4 f6 {, even though the
tactical complications favor White:} 22. Rd6 fxe5 23. f5 $1 Bxf5 (23... gxf5
24. Rxe6 Rxe6 25. Qxd7 $16) 24. g4 Be6 25. Rxe6 Rxe6 26. Qxd7 $16) 20. b3 Qb4
21. Ne2 ({Good enough was also} 21. Na4 Rxa4 22. bxa4 Bxc4 23. Rd8) 21... Re7
22. Nf4 Qa5 23. e5 {Finally this thematic advance makes Black's position
cramped.} Ne8 24. Nxe6 Rxe6 25. f4 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4,Gg3,Rg7]} f6 {Black's pieces
lack harmony, so this break leads to the collapse.} 26. Rd7 Rb8 ({Or} 26...
fxe5 27. Qg4 Rd6 28. Rxd6 Nxd6 29. Qe6+ Nf7 30. f5 $18) 27. Bd2 Qb6 28. Bc3
fxe5 29. Qg4 Rd6 30. fxe5 $2 {This natural recapture is a big mistake that
could have spoiled everything.} ({The following nice line illustrates how
helpless Black was:} 30. Rd1 $1 Nf6 31. R1xd6 Nxg4 32. hxg4 {The material
advantage is currently on Black's side, but White is firmly in control!} Kh8
33. Bd5 Re8 34. Bf7 Rf8 35. fxe5 $18) 30... Rxd7 $2 ({After} 30... h5 $1 31.
Qg5 Rxd7 32. Qxg6 Qc7 {thr result of this game would be unpredictable - Black
is a rook up!}) 31. Qxd7 Qc7 32. Rd1 Rc8 $2 ({It wa still possible to put-up
resistance by means of} 32... Qxd7 33. Rxd7 Bh6 $1 $16) 33. Qe6+ Kh8 34. Rd7
Qb8 35. Qf7 Rd8 36. e6 1-0

