{[%evp 0,99,25,-16,-12,-15,46,17,28,16,16,7,17,26,33,55,77,9,82,31,35,14,29,
-29,16,-2,25,0,12,-3,-13,23,32,30,73,69,76,5,45,47,59,28,20,30,21,21,34,35,18,
32,31,33,37,60,64,28,81,64,123,111,161,151,140,125,125,125,125,52,95,29,139,
238,238,55,60,47,102,74,74,84,84,66,97,74,277,339,339,360,287,287,317,263,313,
313,307,341,352,346,343,421,29999,-30000]} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2
O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4 c6 9. Rb1 $5 {This is one of White's
many options in this line. It is definitely vital to move the rook away from
the a1-h8 diagonal and to make the b3-b4 advance more effective in the long
run.} exd4 10. Nxd4 Re8 {[%cal Yd6d5,Yb7b5,Gf2f4,Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Yd7c5,Yc5e4,Ye8e4,
Yf6e4,Ge4e5] One of Black's main tasks is to put strong pressure on the
e4-pawn, so White's pieces would be tied up with defending it. Furthermore,
the b7-b5 and d6-d5 breaks might help Black to solve his strategic problems.
White's main plan is to extend in the centre with f2-f4 and e4-e5 or to attack
the c6-pawn with b4-b5, but first he has to neutralize Black's counter-play.}
11. h3 {This is a universal prophylactic move which is regularly played in
various KID positions.} Nc5 12. Re1 a5 13. b3 {Another decent prophylactic
move that makes it impossible for Black to play a5-a4 and to subsequently put
his queen on a5. It also slowly prepares White's b3-b4.} Nfd7 $6 {[%cal Gd7e5,
Ge5d3,Gc5d3] This was played with the ambitious idea of occupying the
d3-square in White's camp, but it is not realistic since Black's knights are
very unstable.} ({A better way of handling the position is} 13... h6 {,
maintaining the pressure on the Pe4 and intending to meet} 14. Bf4 (14. f4 {
runs into} d5 $1 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. e5 Nfe4 $132) {with} 14... Nh7 $1 15. Qd2
Ng5 {, when Black has enough activity in order to compensate for the weak Pd6.
For instance,} 16. h4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Nge6 18. Qxd6 Nxf4 19. Qxd8 Rxd8 20. gxf4
Nd3 21. Red1 Be6 {with approximate equality.}) 14. Be3 Ne5 15. Re2 $1 {This
move makes Black's piece play ineffective. White is ready to chase the Be5 and
continue extending.} f5 {Black reasonably does not want to retreat his knight
back, even though this advance is very quite committing.} 16. exf5 Bxf5 17.
Nxf5 gxf5 {[%csl Rd6,Rf5] White has both the bishop pair and the better pawn
structure.} 18. Rc2 $6 ({More natural was} 18. Qc2 $1 Qf6 19. Rd1 Nf7 20. Bd4
$16 {White's superiority is undeniable.}) 18... Ng6 19. Qd2 Qf6 20. f4 $6 {
Vassily neutralizes Black's counter-play connected with ...f5-f4, but at the
same time he also weakens the pawn chain around his own king.} (20. Ne2 Ne4 21.
Qd3 Ne5 22. Qd1 $14) 20... Nh8 $2 {Black wrongly switches to passive defense,
so White is in time to consolidate now.} ({Correct was} 20... h5 $1 21. h4 Nf8
22. Re1 Qg6 23. Bf2 Rxe1+ 24. Bxe1 Re8 $132 {[%csl Rg3] The weak Pg3 offers
Black sufficient counter-play.}) 21. Re1 Nf7 22. Re2 Re7 23. Bf2 Rae8 24. Rxe7
Qxe7 {Black temporarily has control over the e-file, but there are no invasion
squares.} 25. Kh2 Ra8 26. Rc1 Qf6 27. Ne2 Qb2 $2 {The desertion of the Qb2 of
the kingside puts Black in a hopeless situation.} ({Much better was} 27... Re8
28. Nd4 Nh6 $16 {, and White still has to make progress.}) 28. Rc2 Qb1 ({
More stubborn was} 28... Qf6 {, admitting the mistake. However, even then after
} 29. Bd4 Qg6 30. Rc3 Re8 31. Re3 Rxe3 32. Bxe3 $18 {Black's position would
collapse.}) 29. Nd4 Bxd4 30. Bxd4 $18 {Now the king is too exposed.} Re8 31.
Bb2 $6 ({Simpler was} 31. Bxc5 $1 dxc5 32. Rc1 Re2 33. Qxe2 Qxc1 34. Qd3 $18)
31... Kf8 32. Qc3 Re6 33. Bc1 Ne4 34. Qd3 Qa1 35. Bb2 Qb1 36. Qe2 Nc5 37. Qd2
Ne4 $6 (37... Re1 {would still have allowed Robert to put up resistance:} 38.
g4 Qd1 39. Qxd1 Rxd1 40. Bf3 Rd3 41. Be2 Re3 {, and there is plenty of play.})
38. Bxe4 fxe4 39. Qe2 $2 {A serious mistake that could have changed the route
of the game.} ({Correct was} 39. Qc1 Qxc1 40. Bxc1 d5 41. Be3 $18 {Black's
passers are stopped, while White's connected passers should decide the game.})
39... e3 $2 ({Curiously,} 39... Nh6 $1 {would most likely let Black solve all
his problems. For instance,} 40. Rc1 (40. Rd2 e3 41. Rd1 Qe4 $11) 40... Qd3 41.
Re1 Nf5 42. Qxd3 exd3 43. Bc3 Rxe1 44. Bxe1 a4 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gf5d4] with
mutual chances.}) 40. Bd4 $2 {Another step in the wrong direction.} ({It was
possible to liquidate the dangerous passer:} 40. Bc1 $1 c5 41. Rc3 Nd8 42. Bxe3
Nc6 43. Qf2 $18) 40... c5 41. Bc3 Re4 $2 {Luckily for GM Ivanchuk, his
lower-rated opponent did not take his chance.} ({Instead,} 41... h5 $1 42. Rb2
(42. Bxa5 Nh6 43. Bc3 Nf5 $17 {[%cal Gf5d4]}) 42... Qf5 43. Qf3 Qd3 44. Bxa5
Nh6 {would have offered Black excellent counter-play.}) 42. Rb2 Qc1 43. Qd3 {
[%csl Rf7] The Nf7 is out of play, so Black is losing.} Re6 44. Rb1 Qa3 45. f5
Re8 46. f6 Kg8 47. Qf5 {Now Black's king is helpless.} Kh8 48. Qd7 Rf8 49. Qxd6
Nxd6 50. f7# 1-0

