{[%evp 0,71,32,32,35,-13,30,29,40,44,86,43,60,27,33,30,59,9,9,-13,20,1,16,-11,
1,0,46,-25,-5,-18,29,30,24,7,10,6,52,52,40,45,45,45,39,44,86,102,96,84,120,118,
158,155,185,199,186,138,171,176,215,187,187,187,187,231,231,219,973,969,969,
175,196,951,969,1013]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6 3. Nf3 Nbd7 4. Nc3 g6 5. g3 Bg7 6.
Bg2 O-O 7. O-O e5 8. e4 exd4 {Mostly it is tough for Black to deviate from
releasing the tension in the centre for too long as the Bc8 is locked, so he
has to move the queen's knight sooner or later.} 9. Nxd4 Re8 10. h3 Nc5 11. Re1
Bd7 {As usual in this line Black suffers from lack of space, but there are a
few possibilities to complicate the matters. Mostly, his main hopes are
connected with the b7-b5 break or piece play on the kingside (the artificial
Re8-e5-h5 manoeuvre is one of the ideas).} 12. Bf4 h6 {A decent move. Black
does not let White take control over the c1-h6 diagonal, so the Bf4 is
somewhat unstable.} 13. Qc2 {The most common move, which has a clear drawback
because it diminishes White's control of the Nd4.} ({The prophylactic} 13. Kh2
$5 {is a viable alternative.}) 13... Qc8 $6 {A pointless move.} ({Black missed
a golden opportunity of solving his strategic issues with} 13... Nfxe4 $1 14.
Nxe4 Bxd4 15. Qd2 Bg7 16. Nxc5 dxc5 17. Rxe8+ Bxe8 18. Bxh6 Qxd2 19. Bxd2 Rd8
20. Bg5 {This was Vantika, A - Maltsevskaya, A Khanty-Mansiysk 2016 Black
should have played} Rb8 21. Rb1 b5 $1 22. cxb5 Bxb5 {The activity of her
pieces would have offered Black sufficient compensation for her structural
drawbacks.}) 14. Kh2 Ne6 ({Now it was too late for} 14... Nfxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxd4
16. Bxg6 Rxe1 17. Bh7+ Kg7 18. Rxe1 $36) (14... Ng4+ {would not change much
either:} 15. hxg4 Bxd4 16. Bxh6 Bxg4 17. Qd2 $16) 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Nd5 {
Black faces the usual problems: the presence of the Nd5 is very annoying,
while c7-c6 would isolate the d6-pawn.} ({The patient} 16. b3 $5 $16 {also
would have kept all the merits of White's position.}) 16... Nd7 17. Rad1 Ne5
18. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c3,Gf2f4] A decent plan. The exchange of dark-squared
bishops would offer White certain attacking chances. Also, f2-f4 will follow
soon.} c6 $2 {Curiously, this natural move turns out to be a decisive mistake.}
({Black should have played} 18... c5 19. Bc3 Qd8 20. f4 Nc6 $16 {[%cal Gc6d4] ,
and the knight might reach d4.}) 19. Ne3 b5 {A desperate attempt to develop
any counter-play.} ({Now it was too late to re-locate the knight:} 19... c5 20.
Bc3 Qc7 21. f4 Nc6 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Qc3+ f6 24. f5 $1 Bf7 25. fxg6 $18 {
with a decisive attack.}) 20. Bc3 {David's play is very natural and strong.}
bxc4 ({Hardly better was} 20... Nxc4 21. Nxc4 Bxc4 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Rxd6 Qc7
24. Red1 Rad8 25. e5 $18 {with full domination.}) 21. Rxd6 Qc7 ({The most
stubborn was} 21... Nd3 22. Rd1 Bf8 {, though even then after} 23. e5 $1 Bxd6
24. exd6 Rd8 25. b3 {Black's position should crack soon.}) 22. Red1 Rad8 {
Black has too many weaknesses, so the exchange of rooks does not help.} 23.
Rxd8 Rxd8 24. f4 Rxd1 25. Qxd1 Qb6 (25... Nd3 26. f5 Bc8 27. Nxc4 $18) 26. Qd2
Nd3 27. Bxg7 Kxg7 28. f5 $1 $18 {From now on everything is clear.} gxf5 29.
exf5 Bd5 30. Ng4 $1 {The king is helpless.} Kf8 31. Qxh6+ Ke7 32. Qf6+ Kf8 33.
Qd6+ Kg8 34. Nf6+ Kg7 35. Ng4 Kg8 36. Qh6 1-0

