{[%evp 0,77,32,35,35,16,58,32,33,37,36,16,8,26,35,50,90,66,48,45,8,64,88,67,79,
69,83,65,68,53,54,47,45,45,73,82,98,69,64,89,89,73,78,76,71,45,63,55,35,52,58,
55,56,52,59,48,53,46,46,33,120,128,165,165,168,168,158,177,162,185,185,210,225,
240,282,293,343,332,330,327]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. g3 O-O
6. Bg2 c6 7. O-O Qa5 {Even though this is Black's most popular move, it seems
inferior compared to others as the Qa5 rarely turns out to be effective, while
White gains a lot of space.} 8. e4 Bg4 {Another common move that I do not like
because the exchange of light-squared bishop always limits Black's
counter-chances on the kingside.} ({In my opinion,} 8... e5 {has to be
preferred.}) 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 e5 11. d5 cxd5 12. cxd5 (12. exd5) 12... Nbd7
13. Qe2 {A solid choice. My idea was to complete the development and to get
ready to play along the c-file.} ({The more aggressive option is} 13. g4 $5 {
, starting to extend on the kingside. In this case, White's light-squared
bishop might be activated very quickly.}) 13... a6 14. Bd2 Rfc8 15. h4 {
[%cal Gf3g2,Gg2h3] My plan was not to attack on the kingside but to re-route
the light-squared bishop to h3.} h5 16. Bg2 Kh7 {A typical positional approach
as the potential exchange of the dark-squared bishops would partly solve
Black's strategic issues.} 17. Bh3 Qb4 ({More consistent would have been to
play} 17... Bh6 18. Bg5 Rc7 {, even though the exchange might weaken Black's
setup on the kingside. The play might continue:} 19. Qd2 Bxg5 20. hxg5 Ne8 21.
f4 $16 {White's superiority in undeniable.}) 18. f3 Qc4 $2 {A loss of time.} (
18... Qxb2 {runs into} 19. Rab1 Qa3 20. Rxb7 Rab8 21. Bxd7 Rxb7 22. Bxc8 Qc5+
23. Kg2 Qxc8 24. Qxa6 {White should be able to convert his extra pawn into a
full point.}) ({However, more to the point was} 18... Rc7 $16) 19. Rac1 Rc7 20.
Qxc4 Rxc4 21. b3 ({Good enough was also} 21. Ne2 Rac8 22. Bg5 $1 Bh6 23. Kf2 {
, and Black is practically paralyzed.}) 21... Rc7 22. Na4 Rac8 23. Rxc7 Rxc7
24. Rc1 Rxc1+ 25. Bxc1 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7,Gh3] Curiously, this position is
absolutely lost for Black - his pieces desperately lack space, while White's
unopposed light-squared bishop can easily attack the weak pawns on a6 and b7.}
b5 ({Hardly better was} 25... Bh6 26. Bg5 Kg7 27. Nb2 Nb6 28. a4 $1 Bxg5 29.
hxg5 Nh7 30. f4 $18 {with total domination.}) 26. Nb2 Bh6 27. Bg5 Kg7 28. Nd3 {
[%cal Gd3b4,Gb4c6] The knight is en route to c6.} a5 ({The following line is
rather illustrative:} 28... Nb8 29. Bxh6+ Kxh6 30. Kf2 Kg7 31. Ke3 Kf8 32. Kd2
Ke7 33. Kc3 Kd8 34. Kb4 Kc7 35. Ka5 Kb7 36. Nb4 $18 {, and the a2-a4 break
would separate the a6-pawn.}) 29. b4 $1 {[%csl Rb5] Fixing another weakness.}
a4 30. Nc1 Nb6 31. Bxh6+ Kxh6 32. Ne2 Nc4 33. Nc3 Na3 34. Bf1 {Finally the
pawn falls. The rest was just agony.} Nc2 35. Nxb5 Ne8 36. a3 Kg7 37. Kf2 Kf8
38. Bd3 Na1 39. Nc3 1-0

