{[%evp 0,87,25,25,73,39,111,42,42,42,37,10,7,24,23,7,26,26,48,34,52,43,76,42,
42,42,42,15,39,15,-2,-19,-9,-12,-22,-24,2,-9,16,6,1,-3,2,11,67,67,76,64,83,88,
86,97,59,54,60,58,65,42,46,46,40,43,46,35,108,67,72,79,72,135,166,150,187,182,
184,194,223,193,238,212,194,213,293,288,323,309,305,383,751,828]} 1. d4 d6 2.
Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O a6 8. Bf4 $5 {This has
gained popularity in the last 5 years. The bishop is positioned somewhat
awkwardly, but White vacates c1 for the rook so the b7-b5 break would be less
effective. Also, Black has to anticipate Qd1-d2 followed by the exchange of
the powerful Bg7 which would limit his counter-attacking abilities.} Ng4 $6 {
[%cal Ye7e5] Quite a rare response. By making this aggressive move Black tries
to show the drawback of White's last move by preparing e7-e5. However, this
advance does not guarantee Black a comfortable play.} ({The most illustrative
line is:} 8... Rb8 9. Rc1 Bd7 10. Qd2 b5 11. Nd5 {This position was tested in
dozens of games. The pressure along the c-file offers White some advantage.})
9. h3 e5 10. Bg5 {White provokes f7-f6 in order to take this square away from
the Ng4.} f6 11. Bc1 exd4 ({In case of} 11... Nh6 {White can take advantage of
the better piece coordination with} 12. dxe5 dxe5 (12... fxe5 13. Bg5 Qd7 14.
Nd5 Nf7 15. Bf6 {looks really bad for Black.}) 13. Qxd8 Nxd8 14. Nd5 Ne6 15.
Nd2 c6 16. Nb6 Rb8 17. b4 {In this endgame Black's setup is very cramped. Ding,
L - Wen, Y Danzhou 2013}) 12. Nxd4 Nge5 {This was the point of releasing the
tension in the centre as the knight can be positioned in the centre. However,
the pawn structure clearly favours White now.} 13. Nxc6 Nxc6 ({The alternative
-} 13... bxc6 {would be met by} 14. f4 Nf7 15. Bxc6 Bxh3 16. Bxa8 Bxf1 17. Bf3
Bh3 18. Be3 $16 {Black has a couple of weaknesses, while his counter-play on
the kingside does not exist.}) 14. Be3 Be6 15. b3 {We have reached a typical
pawn structure. White has a stable control over the centre and pressure along
the h1-a8 diagonal. It seems unlikely that Black would manage to solve his
space problems by pushing either b7-b5 or d6-d5.} Qd7 16. Kh2 Rae8 (16... f5
17. Qd2 Rae8 18. Rac1 $16) 17. Rc1 Ne7 {Black is getting ready for an
appearance of White's knight on d5 in advance.} 18. Qd3 {At this stage I was
not in a hurry.} ({Good enough was also} 18. Nd5 $5 {provoking} c6 19. Nf4 Bf7
20. Qd2 $16 {The weak Pd6 is a cause of worries, as well as the lack of any
counter-play.}) 18... Qc8 {A sad necessity. The queen is going to be tied up
with covering the Pb7 for a while.} 19. Bd2 {This move was aimed for starting
advancing the ''e'' and ''f'' pawns.} ({Somewhat more energetic was} 19. Nd5 $5
) 19... Nc6 20. Nd5 Ne5 21. Qc2 {The main issue of Boris was the absence of a
constructive plan hence he had to sit and wait.} Bf5 {A desperate decision,
that helps White to make progress.} ({Better was} 21... f5 22. e3 c6 23. Nf4
Bf7 $16) 22. e4 Be6 23. Bc3 ({The immediate} 23. f4 Nd7 24. Bc3 {was equally
good.}) 23... c6 {Eventually Black had to weaken the d6 as the Nd5 was
becoming too annoying.} 24. Ne3 f5 25. f4 Nf7 26. Bxg7 {The exchange of
dark-squared bishop mostly makes Black's king very unsafe.} Kxg7 27. exf5 Bxf5
28. Qc3+ Kg8 29. Rce1 {White is not in a hurry - he can slowly make progress
all over the board.} Bd7 30. b4 b5 $2 {This impulsive decision invites fresh
trouble.} ({Better was} 30... Qd8 31. a4 Re7 $16) 31. a3 Qd8 32. Ng4 $1 {
After exchanging Black's bishop the position is going to collapse.} Bxg4 33.
hxg4 Rxe1 34. Rxe1 bxc4 35. Qxc4 (35. Bxc6 d5 36. Re6 $18 {was equally strong.}
) 35... Qd7 36. Qxc6 Qxg4 37. Qxa6 {The rest is clear.} Qh5+ 38. Kg1 Qg4 39.
Kh2 Qh5+ 40. Kg1 Qg4 41. Qd3 Kg7 42. Qc3+ Kh6 43. Bc6 Qh3 44. Re2 1-0

