{[%evp 0,31,28,28,30,-14,47,10,23,8,8,21,22,30,38,33,31,33,47,12,9,23,19,17,11,
13,25,2,28,38,38,40,37,37]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6
6. Nf3 Bg4 (6... Bf5 {is usually connected with occupying the e4-square, but
here it is less effective in view of} 7. Nh4 {, and the bishop has to go back}
Bc8 8. O-O e5 {Now the least White can do is} 9. Nf3 exd4 (9... Nbd7 {again
transposes to 6... Nbd7.}) 10. Nxd4 Re8 11. h3 Nbd7 12. e4 {, that would take
us to one of the key positions of the 6...Nbd7 file.}) 7. O-O Qc8 {This
somewhat artificial approach was played by a few good players, including the
great Victor Korchnoi. Black gives up the fight in the centre, and aims to
exchange the light-squared bishops.} (7... Nc6 {is covered via 6...Nc6 7.0-0
Bg4.}) 8. Bg5 {I like this way of showing the drawbacks of Black's setup.} ({
The prophylactic} 8. Re1 $5 c5 9. d5 {also looks promising for White.}) 8... h6
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 (9... exf6 {makes it possible to avoid the exchange of
dark-squared bishop, but the arising pawn structure is unfavourable for Black
who struggles to develop any adequate counter-play on the kingside.} 10. b4 Re8
11. c5 Qd7 12. Qb3 $14 {White had great prospects on the queenside in
Rashkovsky, N - Bilek, I Palma de Mallorca 1989}) 10. Nd5 Nd7 {Padevsky,
N-Sznapik, A Warsaw 1985} 11. Qd2 Kg7 12. Ne1 c6 13. Nxf6 Nxf6 14. f3 Bh3 15.
Bxh3 Qxh3 16. Nd3 $14 {White's chances are better due to the superiority in
the centre.} *

