{[%evp 0,33,25,24,24,-11,35,26,16,13,17,17,26,26,22,22,35,57,6,44,63,0,37,2,23,
0,44,44,82,59,42,19,53,-3,19,31]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5.
Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bg4 {This move has been known since 1928, and since
then it has been employed by many great players such as Geller, Petrosian,
Nakamura, Radjabov and more. Black intends to exchange his light-squared
bishop in order to diminish White's control over d4.} 8. d5 ({Less promising
seems} 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nd7 10. e3 e5 11. d5 Ne7 {in this position White's
bishop pair is not that meaningful.}) 8... Na5 ({Clearly worse is} 8... Bxf3 $6
9. exf3 Na5 10. b3 c5 ({The attempt to change the unfavourable route of play
by means of} 10... Nxd5 {fails to:} 11. Nxd5 Bxa1 12. Bd2 $1 c6 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7
14. Qxa1 b6 15. Re1 Qd7 16. Bh6 f5 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 18. f4 {White regained the
material and obtained a huge positional advantage in Bernard, C - Andruet, G
Paris 1989}) 11. Bb2 a6 12. Re1 Re8 13. Qd2 Rb8 14. Nd1 b5 15. Bc3 Nb7 16. Ne3
{Black's position desperately lacked space in Bielicki,C - Glavina,P Argentina
1989}) 9. b3 {I like this way of covering the c4-pawn - there is no reason to
tie the queen to the defence of the pawn.} c5 (9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Bxa1 11. Bd2
Nxc4 {, as in Andersson,U - Gaehler,M Haarlem 2012} ({Or} 11... c6 12. Bxa5
Qxa5 13. Nxe7+ Kg7 14. Qxa1+ f6 15. Nd4 Rae8 16. Nexc6 bxc6 17. Bxc6 $18 {
Cuenca Jimenez,J - Carbonell Sancho,M Roquetas de Mar 2018}) {should be met by}
12. Bg5 $1 Bf6 13. Bxf6 exf6 14. bxc4 c6 15. Ne3 $16 {In the unbalanced
position that arose White is much better since Black has quite a few
weaknesses.}) 10. dxc6 {White allows the liberation of the Na5, but the
arising pawn structure is suitable.} ({Good enough also seems} 10. Bb2 $5 a6
11. Nd2 Rb8 12. Qc2 b5 13. Rae1 {White has a favourable version of the
Yugoslav Variation with sort of an extra tempo since Black played the useless
Bc8-g4.}) 10... bxc6 {This is the most ambitious, and it was recently played
by Hikaru Nakamura twice.} ({Safer looks} 10... Nxc6 {, but it offers White a
long-lasting positional pressure due to the space advantage:} 11. Be3 Qa5 12.
Rc1 Rfc8 ({Dubious is} 12... Qh5 {Abramovic,B - Pantelic,S Paracin 2010 Now
the simple} 13. Nd5 $146 Nxd5 14. cxd5 $16 {would have put Black in a
difficult situation when White's rook enters the 7th rank.}) 13. h3 Bd7 14. Qd2
Rab8 15. Rfd1 {White's superiority was undeniable in Jurek, J - Smejkal, J
Mlada Boleslav 1995}) 11. Bb2 Rb8 12. Qd2 Qc7 13. Rad1 Rfd8 (13... c5 14. Nd5
Nxd5 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. cxd5 $14) 14. h3 Be6 15. Ba1 Nb7 {We have been
following the game Navara, D - Nakamura, H Saint Louis 2017} 16. e4 Nc5 17. Qe3
{would have put Black in a passive position with no real counter-play.} *

