{[%evp 0,33,25,24,34,-11,37,26,26,13,17,17,26,26,22,22,22,21,44,-20,28,17,52,4,
4,-28,26,36,26,40,43,38,62,57,60,31]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O
5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bf5 8. d5 {Like in most lines of the KID with Nc6
White feels comfortable with expanding in the centre with tempo.} ({The are
several decent alternatives such as} 8. Ne1) ({Or} 8. Bg5 $5 {, as was tried
by the current World Champion, but the text still seems more promising.}) 8...
Na5 9. Nh4 {This is only White's 3rd choice by statistics, but I like this
move - the Bc1 remains unlocked, and the standard c7-c5 wouldn't disturb White.
} ({Both} 9. Nd2) ({and} 9. Nd4 {are much more popular.}) 9... Bd7 (9... Nxc4
$6 {obviously runs into} 10. Nxf5 gxf5 11. Qd3 $16) 10. b3 c5 {Like in the
Yugoslav Variation, Black first secures his Na5. From now on attacking the
c4-pawn is Black's main plan.} ({I've also examined} 10... c6 $146 11. Bb2 cxd5
12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxg7 Ne3 ({Even worse is} 13... Kxg7 14. cxd5 b5 15. Qd4+ Kg8
16. Nf3 $16) 14. Qd4 Nxf1 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 16. Rxf1 Nc6 17. Qd2 Qg7 18. Rd1 $14 {
White has a slight, but long-lasting positional pressure.}) ({After} 10... a6
11. Bb2 b5 (11... c5 {transposes to the main line.}) 12. Ne4 $1 Nxe4 13. Bxg7
Kxg7 14. Bxe4 c5 15. Qd2 $36 {White has excellent attacking prospects on the
kingside, while Black's pieces are very passive and the Na5 is stuck.}) ({
