invites more troubles:} 10. cxd5 Bxc3 11. Bh6 Bxa1 12. Qxa1 Ne5 13. Nxe5 dxe5
14. h3 Bd7 15. f4 $1 $40) 10. a3 Na6 11. Be3 Nc5 12. Bd4 a5 13. b4 Na6 14. Rb1
$14) (8... Bf5 {In comparison to 7...Bf5, White is practically a tempo up
since Ra8-b8 is pointless here.} 9. Bb2 Ne4 10. Rc1 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 e5 12. d5 Ne7
13. Nd2 Qd7 {This position was reached in Fridman, D - Lagarde, M Belgium 2019
Now White should have played} 14. f4 $1 exf4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Rxf4 $16 {
, putting Black under strong pressure on the kingside.}) (8... e5 {As after 7..
.a6 8.b3 e5, White now takes the opportunity of liquidating into a comfortable
endgame.} 9. dxe5 dxe5 ({Clearly worse is} 9... Nxe5 $2 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Ba3
Re8 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Rad1 {, and Black faces big problems with covering the
back-rank.}) 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Rad1 Bg4 ({Hardly better is} 12...
Bf5 13. Nh4 Bg4 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. f3 Bh3 16. Rxd8+ Rxd8 17. Rd1 {White has a
stable advantage due to the better pawn structure.}) 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nd4
15. Bg2 Bf8 16. Bb2 {It definitely makes sense to maintain the bishop pair.} c6
17. e3 Ne6 18. Na4 Nd7 19. Bc3 $14 {Black was doomed to passive defence in
