{[%evp 0,35,20,23,30,-11,55,7,19,8,8,31,16,4,36,15,39,18,9,19,9,-31,-3,-53,36,
24,16,-10,10,-1,31,46,46,13,13,18,16,16]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2
O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O e5 {This natural move was first seen almost a
century ago. The position that arises after 8.d5 Ne7 is very similar to the
Classical Variation of the KID (with White's bishop on e2), and it proved to
be very comfortable for White. The main reason is that Black often fails to
develop adequate play on the queenside with Nh5 and f7-f5, whereas White has
decent prospects on the queenside. However, a few years ago the KID players
found a fresh attractive idea: 8.d5 Nb8!?, when Black manages to set-up a
blockade and solve most of his problems.} 8. dxe5 $5 {This looks less
challenging than 8.d5, but it is justified by the fact that White's
light-squared bishop is getting very powerful.} dxe5 (8... Nxe5 {can be well
met by} 9. b3 $5 {White is satisfied with the pawn structure, so he just has
to neutralize the opponent's activity.} Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 Ne4 {This tempting move
invites simplifications.} ({After} 10... Bh3 11. Re1 c6 12. Be3 $146 ({But not
} 12. Bb2 $6 d5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 {, and Black is fine.}) 12... Re8 13. Qd2 Qa5 14.
Bd4 $14 {[%csl Rd6] Black does not have any compensation for the weak Pd6.})
11. Nxe4 Bxa1 12. Bg5 f6 13. Bh6 {White easily regains material.} Be5 14. Bxf8
Qxf8 15. Bg2 f5 16. Ng5 c6 (16... Qe7 {does not change much:} 17. Qd2 Bf6 18.
h4 $14 {Avrukh,B - Liang,A Chicago 2017}) 17. Qd2 h6 {This position took place
in Grandelius,N - Kukk,S internet 2018 At this moment White had no reason for
rejecting the most natural} 18. Nf3 $146 Bf6 19. Rd1 {, keeping Black under
strong pressure.}) 9. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5] The pin along the h4-d8 diagonal
creates definite problems for Black. In particular, White is threatening to
play Nc3-d5 to attack the c7-pawn.} Be6 {The most natural response - Black
covers d5 by developing the bishop.} ({After} 9... h6 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Bxf6
Bxf6 12. Nd5 Bg7 ({After} 12... Kg7 13. Nxc7 Rb8 14. e4 g5 15. Nd5 $14 {
Black did not have much for the pawn in Grkinic, G - Garcia Rojas, H email 2003
}) 13. Nxc7 Rb8 14. Rad1 {The bishop pair does not provide Black with
sufficient compensation for the pawn. For instance,} e4 (14... Bf5 15. Nd5 e4
16. Nd2 $14 {Baughman,L-Kearns,J USA 1998}) 15. Rxd8+ Nxd8 16. Nd2 f5 17. b3
$14) (9... Qxd1 {is a certain concession since it helps White to take control
over the open file.} 10. Rfxd1 h6 11. Be3 $1 {It definitely makes sense to
keep the dark-squared bishop on the board.} Be6 (11... Kh7 {, as in Halkias, S
- Bocharov, D Riyadh 2017 can be naturally met by} 12. Nd5 $146 Ne8 13. Bc5 Rg8
14. Ne1 Be6 15. Rac1 f5 16. e4 {White has a stable advantage due to the better
coordination between the pieces.}) 12. Nd5 e4 {This position occurred in Csala,
I - Horvath,L Hungary 2006 At this moment White should have played:} 13. Nxf6+
$146 Bxf6 14. Nd2 Bxb2 15. Rab1 Bg7 16. Rxb7 $14) ({Too artificial seems} 9...
Qe8 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. cxd5 Nd4 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Rc1 {The pressure along the
c-file was very annoying for Black in Bakshi,R - Salonika,S Pune 2014}) 10. Qc1
{I like this multi-tasking move. White secures his Bg5 and vacates d1 for the
rook.} (10. Qa4 {is the common alternative.}) 10... Qc8 {Avoiding the nasty
pin is the best Black can do.} ({The tactical point of White's last move is
illustrated in the following line:} 10... Bxc4 $6 11. Nd2 Be6 12. Nde4 Nd4 {
Sprecic,M - Nurkic,S Tuzla 2003} (12... Qe7 $2 13. f4 $18) 13. e3 Nf5 14. Rd1
Qe7 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. Rxd5 $16 {White regains the pawn under favorable
circumstances.}) ({The awkward} 10... Qb8 {does not look like an improvement:}
11. Rd1 Nd7 12. Bh6 f6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. b3 Rf7 15. Qb2 $14 {Black suffered
from a lack of harmony in Vidit,S - Naiditsch, A Hungary 2017}) (10... Qe8 11.
Rd1 Nd7 {, as in Erdos,V - Ivic,V Skopje 2018 also should be met by} 12. b3
$146 f6 13. Bh6 $14) 11. Rd1 {Now Black is at a crossroad. We will consider a
few natural possibilities:} Rd8 {The exchange of rooks is aimed for
re-locating the poor Qc8.} ({Too passive is} 11... Nd7 12. b3 f6 ({The more
aggressive} 12... f5 13. Bh6 Nf6 14. Nd5 e4 {might invite big trouble:} 15.
Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Ng5 Bxd5 17. cxd5 Nd8 18. Qc3 h6 19. h4 $1 $16 {White dominates
over the board.}) 13. Bh6 Rf7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Ne1 h5 16. h4 Nd4 17. e3 Nf5
18. Nd3 $14 {Black lacked any counterplay in Petrosyan,M - Priasmoro,N
Manavgat 2018}) ({The attempt to release the pressure by exchanging the
bishops with} 11... Bh3 {runs into} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nd5 Bg7 ({The
materialistic approach -} 13... Bd8 14. Qh6 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qg4 $6 {Vallejo Pons,
F - Pavlidis,A Tallinn 2016} ({Better was} 15... f6 {, but also then after} 16.
h4 Qg4 17. Rac1 Rf7 18. Qe3 $14 {Black's position seems very passive.}) {
can ne punished by means of} 16. Ne3 $1 Qe4 17. Rd7 $18 {The control over the
7th rank yields White a decisive advantage.}) 14. Bxh3 Qxh3 15. Nxc7 Rac8 16.
Nd5 Rce8 {We have been following the game O'Donnell,C - Collins,S Dublin 2019}
({Hardly better is} 16... e4 17. Ng5 Qg4 18. Qf4 Qxf4 19. Nxf4 $14) {At this
point White could have consolidated by means of} 17. Qe3 $1 $146 e4 18. Nd4 Ne5
(18... Nxd4 $2 19. Rxd4 Bxd4 20. Qxd4 Re6 21. Nf4 $18) 19. Nf4 Qc8 20. Rac1 $14
{, retaining the extra pawn.}) (11... Re8 {was recently tested on GM level} 12.
Nd5 Nd7 13. Bh6 f6 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Black's position looks cramped, but if he
manages to chase the Nd5 and connect his rooks the problems would be solved.
Therefore, I suggest the energetic} 15. b4 $5 $146 ({Instead,} 15. b3 Nd8 16.
Nd2 Nf7 {was equal in Yakubboev,N - Wang Hao Makati 2018}) 15... Nd8 ({After} 
15... Bxd5 16. cxd5 Nxb4 17. Nd2 $36 {White's pressure on the Pc7 outweighs
Black's extra pawn.}) 16. Qa3 c6 17. Rac1 $1 {The poor location of Black's
pieces makes it possible for White to maintain the tension.} Qb8 18. Ne3 Nf7
19. Nd2 $14 {White's superiority is undeniable.}) 12. Rxd8+ ({Weaker is} 12.
Nd2 a5 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nde4 Bg7 15. Rxd8+ Qxd8 16. Nc5 Bc8 $11 {Dragun,K -
Aryan,C Biel 2018}) 12... Qxd8 13. Ne4 Bf5 ({In case of} 13... Qe7 {White can
successfully regroup his forces with} 14. Nfd2 $1 Bf5 15. e3 h6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6
17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Ne4 Qe7 19. Nc3 $14 {The permanent pressure along the h1-a8
diagonal put Black in a passive position in Gledura, B - Aryan, C Budapest 2018
}) 14. Nfd2 h6 $146 {This natural move is a novelty. However, I found it the
most challenging - avoiding the pin is Black's main task.} ({The only
preceding game saw} 14... Nd4 15. Qd1 Bg4 (15... h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. e3 Nc6
18. Qb3 $14) 16. f3 Bf5 17. e3 Nc6 18. Qb3 $14 {The pin was still a cause of
worries in Mchedlishvili,M - Akhvlediani,I Batumi GEO 2018}) 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16.
Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Ne4 Bxe4 18. Bxe4 {[%csl Ge4] The superiority of the Be4 over
Black's knight offers White a small, but long-lasting positional advantage.} *

