the poor coordination between his pieces in Kozusek, D - Swayams, M Pardubice
CZE 2018}) 7. Qa4 $1 {By making this move White forces Black to recapture with
the queen, so it will give him another tempo.} Qxc5 8. Be3 Qc7 (8... Qh5 9. Nh3
Nc6 10. Nf4 Qe5 11. Nfd5 {was clearly better for White in Clarac,J - Bry,S
France 2006}) ({Another natural retreat} 8... Qf5 {can also be met by} 9. Nh3
$5 $146 ({Instead,} 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. O-O d6 11. Nd4 Qh5 {was unclear in Santos
Latasa, J - Abdumalik, Z Llucmajor ESP 2018}) 9... d6 10. Nf4 Bd7 11. Qd1 Bc6 (
11... Nc6 12. O-O Ng4 13. Bd2 $14) 12. Nfd5 Nxd5 13. cxd5 Bd7 14. Bd4 $14 {
White has the more harmonious setup, when Black struggles to find a good
square for his knight.}) 9. Nh3 {This is the most flexible way of development
- the presence of White's knight on d5 would always put Black under pressure.}
d6 10. Nf4 Bd7 (10... Nc6 11. O-O Bd7 12. c5 dxc5 13. Bxc5 $36) 11. Nfd5 Nxd5
12. Nxd5 Qd8 13. Qa3 Nc6 ({I have also examined} 13... Bc6 14. O-O Nd7 15. Rad1
Nb6 {, and now} 16. c5 $1 Nc4 17. Qb3 Nxe3 18. Nxe3 $14 {puts Black under
strong pressure along the d-file.}) 14. O-O Nd4 {We have been following the
game Vidit, S - Narayanan, S Moscow RUS 2018 At this moment I suggest the
following new idea:} 15. Qd3 $1 $146 Bf5 16. Qd2 Nc2 17. Bg5 $1 f6 18. Bxf6 $1
Bxf6 ({Worse is} 18... exf6 $6 19. Rac1 Re8 20. e4 Bxe4 21. Bxe4 Rxe4 22. Qxc2
$16) 19. Nxf6+ Rxf6 20. Rac1 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4] After e2-e4 White would regain
the piece and retain his structural advantage.} *

