{[%evp 0,43,20,23,30,-3,54,4,24,8,31,15,16,18,36,41,32,10,17,15,46,23,37,23,47,
35,46,33,27,27,37,26,23,19,21,18,40,7,44,36,53,40,50,21,28,25]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 c5 7. O-O Nc6 8. dxc5 dxc5 9. Bf4 Nh5
{This natural move is also common. Black forces White to move his bishop away
from the h2-b8 diagonal and unlocks his strong Bg7. On the flip side, now the
Nh5 is out of play.} ({The ambitious} 9... Qa5 {[%cal Gf8d8] , intending to
play 10...Rd8 can be well met by} 10. Nd2 ({Somehow, the most popular} 10. Ne5
Nd4 11. Nd3 Bf5 {does not look very convincing, as Black's pieces are rather
active.}) 10... Rd8 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Nd4 13. e3 Nf5 {This was Orso, M -
Kaposztas, M Hajduszoboszlo 1987 My new natural idea here is} 14. e4 Nd4 15.
Re1 Qb5 16. Rb1 $14 {White's chances seem preferable due to the strong pawn
centre.}) ({Too passive is} 9... Bd7 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Qc8 {[%cal Gd7c6]
Black is trying to neutralize the pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal with
Bd7-c6, but it is too artificial.} 12. Qb3 Bc6 13. e4 Rd8 14. f4 e6 15. Rad1
Ng4 {This position was reached in Ribli, Z - Hulak, K Surakarta 1982 At this
moment White missed a great opportunity of extending his initiative with} 16.
Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Nd5 $1 exd5 18. cxd5 Bd7 19. Qc3+ f6 20. h3 Nh6 21. g4 $40 {
Black struggles to withstand such a massive attack.}) ({If Black continues to
copy the moves with} 9... Bf5 {, then} 10. Ne5 {sets serious problems. For
instance,} Nd4 (10... Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Qb6 {Khetsuriani,B - Makka,E Kallithea
2002 meets} 12. e4 $1 Be6 13. b3 Rad8 14. Qe2 $16) 11. e3 Ne6 12. Qb3 Rb8 13.
Rad1 Qc8 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Nxf4 16. exf4 Qc7 17. Rfe1 {Black's position
was cramped in the correspondence game Yloenen, O - Kain, A email 2014}) (9...
Nd7 {was tried few times by GM Zapata. Black unlocks the Bg7, but interrupts
the development of his queenside pieces} 10. Qc1 Nd4 11. Rd1 e5 (11... Re8 12.
Nxd4 cxd4 {Lagunow,A - Ax,P Porz 1991 runs into} 13. Nb5 $1 e5 14. Bh6 Qb6 15.
Bxg7 Kxg7 16. a4 a5 17. e3 $16 {, and Black's queenside pieces are stuck.}) 12.
Bh6 $16 {White had a huge positional advantage in Siegel, G - Birnbaum,D
Germany 1992}) 10. Be3 {There are a few alternatives, but this retreat seems
most challenging.} Nd4 {The strong Nd4 is supposed to restrict the mobility of
White's heavy pieces.} ({The quieter} 10... b6 {is well met by} 11. Qc1 $1 {
This move is connected with a concrete idea.} Bb7 12. Bh6 {The exchange of
dark-squared bishop would put Black's king in some danger.} ({Less precise
seems} 12. Rd1 Qc8 13. Bh6 Rd8 14. Rxd8+ Qxd8 15. Bxg7 Nxg7 16. Ng5 h6 17. Nge4
Kh7 {Black was close to reaching equality in Bielmeier,L - Lippert,F Bayern
2013}) 12... Qc8 {Black struggles to find a good square for his queen where it
would not interrupt the connection between his rooks.} ({Perhaps, a better try
is} 12... e6 13. Rd1 Qe7 14. g4 Nf6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qf4 {, but also then
White retains the pressure.}) 13. Bxg7 Nxg7 14. Rd1 Rd8 {This was Kirov -
Ribli, Nice ol 1974 Now White missed an opportunity of developing the
initiative on the kingside by means of} 15. Nd5 $1 f6 16. e4 Kh8 17. e5 $36 {
Black's position is cramped, and the Kh8 is rather unsafe.}) 11. Qd2 {
Connecting the rooks and intending to increase the pressure on the centralized
knight.} ({The tempting} 11. Na4 {seems weaker in view of} Bf5 $1 {, and then}
12. Nxc5 Nc2 13. Qxd8 Raxd8 {offers Black a decent counter-play.}) 11... Bg4 (
11... Be6 $6 12. Rfd1 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 {was bad for Black in Poch, C-Pirotzky, M
Pinamar 1974}) ({Hardly better is} 11... e5 12. Nd5 Nf6 (12... Rb8 {, as in
Cherepkov, A-Petrosian, T Soviet Union 1974 should be met by} 13. b4 $1 b6 14.
bxc5 bxc5 15. Rab1 {, and White seizes the initiative.}) 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Bg5
$36 {[%csl Rf6] The pinned Nf6 was a cause of worries in Drygalov, S - Jones,
G St Petersburg RUS 2018}) 12. Rfd1 Bxf3 (12... e5 {, as in Bejtovic,J -
Danielsen,H Copenhagen 2009 can be well met by} 13. Rab1 $146 Rc8 14. b4 b6 15.
bxc5 bxc5 16. Rb7 {, seizing the initiative.}) 13. Bxf3 ({Instead,} 13. exf3 e5
14. Nd5 {Arkell, K - Morowietz, I Hastings 1988 seems less attractive for
White in view of} Nf6 $1 15. f4 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 exf4 17. Bxf4 Qd7 {[%csl Gd4] ,
and the strong Nd4 makes it possible for Black to maintain the balance.}) 13...
Nxf3+ 14. exf3 Qxd2 ({After} 14... b6 15. Qc2 $146 ({Weaker is} 15. Qe2 Qc7 16.
Rd3 Bxc3 17. Rxc3 Rfd8 $11 {Arkell,K - Hebden,M Barnsdale 1989}) 15... Qe8 (
15... Qc7 $6 {now runs into} 16. Nd5 Qb7 17. Qe4 $1 Kh8 18. Qxe7 Qxe7 19. Nxe7
Bxb2 20. Rab1 Bf6 21. Nd5 Bg7 22. a4 $16) 16. Rd3 Rd8 17. Rad1 Rxd3 18. Qxd3
$14 {White takes full control over the only open file.}) 15. Rxd2 Bxc3 ({
The careless} 15... b6 $6 {was seen in a couple of games. Now my improvement
over White's play is:} 16. Nd5 e6 17. Ne7+ Kh8 18. g4 Nf6 19. Rad1 $16) 16.
bxc3 b6 {If Black would manage to neutralize the activity of White's rooks he
would be OK, to say the least. Therefore, White has to play very energetically.
} 17. Rd7 Rfe8 18. Bh6 $1 {This restricting move makes it possible for White
to retain the pressure.} (18. Rad1 $6 {lets Black get his knight back into
play:} Ng7 19. Kf1 Ne6 $11 {Geller, E-Gligoric,S Stockholm 1962}) 18... Ng7 19.
g4 Ne6 20. Re1 $1 {Black rooks are tied with covering the pawns now.} a6 21. a4
Rad8 22. Rd5 $14 {Black can hardly deviate from capturing the Rd5 eventually,
