{[%evp 0,39,29,23,30,-3,43,4,31,8,26,17,16,27,27,27,32,17,15,15,17,17,80,30,30,
38,41,59,56,45,45,21,43,43,56,26,26,27,25,25,34,31]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 c5 {This move invites White to enter the
Benoni with 7.d5. Since it does not match our repertoire, we will focus on
another continuation.} 7. O-O Nc6 {So, Black insists on the closed type of
position by provoking White to push d4-d5.} (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {might lead
us to a well-known theoretical position that often arises from English. The
critical line seems to be} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc6 Rb8 11. Bg2 Qa5 {, and now
White can try} 12. Qd2 $5 Be6 13. b3 Rxb3 14. axb3 Qxa1 15. Nb5 a6 16. Na7 {
White's knight reaches c6, so Black definitely has some concrete problems to
solve here. For instance,} Nd7 17. Nc6 Re8 {This was Efimenko, Z - Melkumyan,
H Warsaw 2016 Now White could have shown his superiority by means of} 18. Qc2
$1 $146 Qc3 19. Qxc3 Bxc3 20. Bg5 $14) 8. dxc5 dxc5 {In this semi-open
symmetric position the extra tempo has value since White is the first to take
control over the central squares.} 9. Bf4 {I believe this is the most
ambitious continuation. White completes the development and gets ready for
occupying the e5-square. At this moment Black has a wide choice of
possibilities.} Be6 {The most common response. Indeed, what could be more
natural than developing the bishop with a tempo?} (9... Nd4 {Among Black's
possibilities, this is the most ambitious way of handling the position. Black
enters the centre first at the cost of leaving his Bc8 on its initial square.}
10. Re1 $1 {The main point of this deep prophylactic move is to make the
Bf4-e5 move possible after Black plays Nf6-h5.} ({White achieves nothing
special with} 10. Be5 Nc6 {, and then the Be5 has to move again. For instance,}
11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bc7 Rd7 13. Bf4 Nh5 14. Be3 Na5 15. Nd2 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Rc7 {
White's bishop pair was compensated by Black's better pawn structure in Costa
Trillo, V - Hjorth, J email 2013}) 10... Be6 (10... Re8 11. Rc1 {Another
useful move which makes White's position more flexible.} Ng4 {Black is trying
to change the unfavourable route of play, but this looks dubious.} ({The other
merit of 10.Re1 can be seen in the following case:} 11... Be6 12. e3 Nxf3+ 13.
Bxf3 $36 {, and now Black got no time for capturing the Pc4.}) 12. h3 e5 13.
Bg5 $1 Nxf3+ 14. exf3 Qxg5 15. fxg4 {White was much better due to the full
control over the light squares in Matlakov, M - Jones, G Wijk aan Zee NED 2018}
) ({Too artificial is} 10... Bf5 11. Nh4 Bc8 12. Be5 Qb6 13. b3 $14 {Black is
doomed to passive defence.}) 11. b3 Nh5 ({After} 11... h6 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Na4
Nh5 14. Bd2 Qc7 15. Qc1 g5 16. Qa3 Rac8 17. Rac1 $14 {the strong Bg2 and the
pawn majority offer White great prospects on the queenside.}) 12. Be5 $1 Nxf3+
13. exf3 Bxe5 14. Rxe5 Qxd1+ 15. Rxd1 b6 16. f4 Rad8 17. Bd5 $14 {Despite
major simplifications, Black's defensive task is not easy since all of White's
pieces are much more active.}) 10. Ne5 Na5 {This is the only way to cover the
b7-pawn and avoid the damage of pawn structure.} ({After} 10... Nh5 11. Nxc6
bxc6 12. Be3 Qxd1 ({After} 12... Rb8 13. Qc2 Qa5 14. Bd2 Qa6 15. b3 $16 {
Black had no compensation for his awful pawn structure in Larsen, B-Johannsson,
I Copenhagen 1956}) 13. Rfxd1 Rab8 14. Bxc5 Rxb2 15. Rac1 Bxc3 16. Rxc3 Rxe2
17. a3 $1 $14 {White managed to regain the pawn under favourable circumstances
in Downey, K - Gravett, A Vale 2016}) ({The exchange makes the pressure along
the h1-a8 diagonal stronger:} 10... Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Nd7 (11... Bxc4 12. Bxb7 Qxd1
13. Rfxd1 Rad8 14. b3 Be6 15. Ba6 {led to a difficult endgame for Black with a
couple of weaknesses in Wastney, S - White, M England 1999}) 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13.
Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bd5 Bh3 15. Re1 Rxb2 16. Na4 $1 {An important tactical resource.}
Rb8 17. Nxc5 e6 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. Bf3 {White had a free pawn in Tkachiev, V -
Dworakowska, J Coventry 2005}) 11. Qe1 $1 {[%cal Ga1d1,Ye1a5] I was surprised
to discover that this logical move was only tested in a few games so far.
White vacates d1 for the rook while the Qe1 keeps an eye on the Na5, so Black
is under definite pressure now.} (11. Qa4 {is by far White's most common
choice, but the Qa4 turns out to be misplaced after} Nd7 $1 {For instance,} 12.
Nxd7 Bxd7 13. Qc2 Nc6 14. Rad1 Qc8 15. Rd2 Bh3 16. Rfd1 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 b6 {
Black solved all his problems in Bocharov, D - Gordievsky, D Kaliningrad 2015})
({Another natural continuation} 11. Qc2 {also seems less effective in view of}
Nh5 12. Rad1 Qe8 13. Nd5 Nxf4 14. gxf4 Rc8 15. Rd2 f6 16. Nf3 Nc6 {with equal
chances. Tukmakov,V - Spraggett,K Bern 1995}) 11... Nh5 {We got a unique
situation where both of Black's knights are on the rim, so the control over
the central squares is diminished. However, liquidating the dark-squared
bishop partly compensates for it.} ({Worse is} 11... Ne8 $6 12. Nd3 $1 {
[%cal Gd3c5] By attacking the Pc5 White manages to show the drawbacks of
Black's awkward setup.} ({Instead,} 12. Rd1 Nd6 13. Nd3 Naxc4 14. Nxc5 Nxb2 $1
{led to unclear play in Miserendino,A - Flores,D Villa Martelli 2004}) 12... b6
(12... Nxc4 13. Nxc5 {is practically lost for Black from a positional point of
view.}) 13. b3 ({The ''greedy''} 13. Bxa8 $2 {should be rejected:} Qxa8 14. f3
Nxc4 $44) 13... Rc8 14. Rd1 Nd6 15. Be5 $16 {White is dominating over the
board.}) ({The natural} 11... Nd7 $146 {has not occured in pratice yet. In my
opinion, White can try} 12. Rd1 $5 Bxe5 13. Bxe5 Nxc4 14. Bf4 Nxb2 15. Rb1 Nc4
16. Qc1 {, obtaining a powerful initiative for the pawns.}) 12. Rd1 Qb6 13. b3
Rad8 ({I've also examined} 13... Nxf4 14. gxf4 Rad8 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. cxd5 Qc7
17. Qc3 b6 18. Qg3 $14 {White's chances are better due to his space advantage
and the strong Ne5.}) 14. Na4 (14. Nd5 $5 Bxd5 15. cxd5 {might get us back to
above-mentioned note.}) 14... Qb4 15. Nd3 Qxe1 16. Rfxe1 Nxf4 17. Nxf4 b6 18.
Nxe6 fxe6 {This was Tempone,M - Flores,D Buenos Aires 1997 White should have
played} 19. Kf1 Rd6 20. e3 $14 {Both Na5 and Na4 are stuck on the side line,
but Black is also suffering from poor the pawn structure on the kingside.} *

