1,7,8,12,11,34,-84,45,-29]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6
6. Nf3 c6 7. O-O Na6 {This move was tried by strong KID players, but it looks
too artificial.} (7... a6 {The idea of ...b7-b5 looks provocative at such an
early stage of the game, so it is not popular on GM level.} 8. e4 b5 9. e5 {
Of course, White is happy to expand in the centre and unlock the h1-a8
diagonal.} Ne8 10. exd6 Nxd6 11. c5 Nf5 12. Ne2 h5 (12... Be6 13. g4 Nh6 14. h3
Bd5 15. Nc3 {White was much better in Gebigke, M - Schulze, U Pforzheim 1997})
13. Re1 Be6 {We have been following the game Filippov, V -Gelman, A Moscow
1995 At this moment I like the following ambitious idea:} 14. a4 $5 b4 15. Bg5
Bd5 16. Nf4 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nxd4 18. Qd3 $36 {Black is under enormous pressure
and the extra pawn does not tell.}) (7... Qb6 {By making this move Black tries
to put pressure on the d4-pawn.} 8. e4 {There are a few more promising options,
but I like this ambitious choice.} Bg4 9. Rb1 {White covers the b2-pawn, so
the bishop can be developed now.} Nfd7 {This is the most consistent.} ({
Too artificial looks} 9... Qa6 10. b3 b5 $6 11. cxb5 cxb5 {Anchutin, N -
Solovjev, N Moscow 2016 Indeed, White can exploit the vulnerability of the
long diagonal by means of} 12. e5 dxe5 13. dxe5 Nfd7 14. h3 Bf5 15. Nd4 Bxb1
16. Bxa8 $16) 10. Be3 c5 11. dxc5 ({Only not} 11. d5 $6 Ne5 {[%cal Rf3d1,Rg4d1]
, and the pin is very annoying.}) 11... dxc5 12. Nd5 Qd8 {From a static point
of view, Black's position looks fine but after White's next move the delay in
development starts to tell} 13. Qb3 $1 b6 ({Hardly better is} 13... Bxf3 $146
14. Bxf3 b6 15. Bg2 e6 16. Nc3 Nc6 17. f4 Nd4 18. Qa4 $14) ({I have also
examined} 13... e6 $146 14. Qxb7 exd5 15. Qxa8 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Ne5 17. Bxc5 $1 ({
Black's idea would be fully justified after} 17. Bg2 $2 d4 18. Bd2 $2 Qc7 19.
Qd5 Rd8 {[%csl Rd5] , and the queen is trapped.}) 17... Nxf3+ 18. Kg2 Nd7 19.
Qxd5 Nxc5 20. Qxd8 Rxd8 21. Kxf3 $16 {White has too many passers.}) 14. Nd2 Nc6
15. h3 Be6 16. f4 Nd4 {We have been following the game Karpov, A - Damljanovic,
B Valjevo 2007 At this moment White should have liquidated the only active
piece of the opponent:} 17. Bxd4 $1 cxd4 (17... Bxd4+ 18. Kh2 Nb8 19. Nf3 Nc6
20. Rbd1 $36) 18. e5 Nc5 19. Qa3 $36 {Black's position is very passive.}) 8. e4
e5 {This is the best attempt to justify Black's previous move.} (8... Nc7 $6 9.
h3 Rb8 10. a4 a6 11. a5 {is just much better for White. For instance,} d5 12.
e5 Nd7 {Guldberg,T-Petersen,E Aalborg 1995} 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. h4 $16 {White
just dominates over the board.}) 9. h3 {A universal move for all KID lines -
White prevents a possible pin and secures the e3 square for his bishop.} Qb6 {
Only this has an independent value.} (9... exd4 10. Nxd4 Re8 11. Be3 Nc5 12.
Qc2 {is covered via the 6...Nbd7 move order.}) 10. Rb1 $5 {This is only
White's 5th choice by statistics, but I find this move very logical - the
b2-b4 advance would claim the drawbacks of Black's setup.} exd4 (10... Qb4 {
was tried once in Antunes,A - Bologan,V Wijk aan Zee 1996 I suggest the simple}
11. Qe2 $5 $146 exd4 12. Nxd4 Re8 13. Nc2 Qa5 14. Rd1 $14 {Black does not have
any compensation for his weak Pd6.}) 11. Nxd4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Bxd4 {This
