{[%evp 0,41,19,9,28,-1,54,11,33,15,22,27,23,30,37,31,93,66,102,35,44,-10,-51,
25,-16,-31,28,28,35,25,46,9,31,24,24,32,40,28,30,30,21,38,41,52]} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 c6 7. O-O Qa5 {This is Black's
most common choice after 6...c6. There are a few points behind this early
queen move: in some cases, the queen stands well on h5 where it puts some
pressure on White's king, but it can also support the b7-b5 break.} 8. e4 {
There are a couple of other interesting options, but I believe this is the
most challenging reply - White has full control over the centre now.} e5 ({
Consistent is} 8... Qh5 {, but the delay in the development of the queenside
pieces start to tell now} 9. e5 {I like this natural reaction - White
liquidates into a comfortable endgame with a space advantage.} (9. Ng5 $5 {
, as suggested by GM Avrukh in his famous 1.d4 repertoire book is another
attractive option.}) 9... dxe5 (9... Ne8 10. Re1 $16) 10. Nxe5 Qxd1 ({Worse is
} 10... Ng4 $6 11. Nf3 Rd8 ({After} 11... Nh6 12. Re1 Bg4 13. Bxh6 Qxh6 14.
Rxe7 Nd7 15. Qb3 {Black did not have any compensation for the pawn in Hoffmann,
A - Baeumler,I Germany 2009}) 12. h3 Nf6 {This position took place in a couple
high-level games. Now I mostly like the following aggressive idea:} 13. g4 $1
$146 (13. Ne5 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Nbd7 15. Be3 {was also clearly better for White in
Banusz,T - Markos,J Austria 2012}) 13... Qa5 (13... Nxg4 {is brilliantly met by
} 14. Ne2 $1 Nf6 (14... Nh6 15. Bg5 $18 {is about the same.}) 15. Bg5 {, and
Black loses a piece in view of the poor location of the Qh5:} Bxh3 16. Nf4 Qg4
17. Nxh3 $18) 14. Re1 Qc7 15. Bg5 Be6 16. Qe2 {White dominates over the board.}
) 11. Rxd1 Nbd7 ({Or} 11... Ng4 12. Nf3 Nd7 13. h3 Ngf6 14. b3 Re8 15. Bf4 $16
{Dorfman,J - Desbonnes,S Clichy 1997}) 12. f4 Nxe5 13. fxe5 Nd7 14. c5 Re8 15.
b4 {Black's position was very cramped in Ruck,R - Szuk,B Hungary 2010}) ({
The move} 8... Bg4 {is dubious since Black is giving his light-squared bishop
away, without obtaining a visible compensation.} 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 e5 ({
Worse is} 10... Nfd7 {when White can just play} 11. Be3 {White completes the
development and is ready to expand on the queenside by means of a2-a3 followed
by b2-b4.} c5 ({After} 11... Qb4 {White can just play the simple which
connects the rooks and prepares Rab1 in a case of ...Qxb2.} 12. Qd3) 12. e5
cxd4 13. Bxd4 dxe5 (13... Nc6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. exd6 e5 16. Be3 $16) 14. Be3
$16) 11. d5 cxd5 12. cxd5 $14 {This position is explained in my game against
Srebrnic which can be found in Typical Pawn Structures section. In this
structure, Black cannot develop a kingside attack due to the absence of his
light-squared bishop. At the same time White has an easy play on the queenside
- the c-file is open and the d6-pawn is rather weak. Furthermore, we shall
mention that every endgame would be practically hopeless for Black.}) ({
The provocative} 8... Be6 {definitely cannot be recommended:} 9. d5 Bg4 10. h3
Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nfd7 (11... Rc8 12. Bd2 Nfd7 13. Be2 Qb6 14. Rb1 a5 {, as in
Blagojevic,D - Arsovic,G Vrnjacka Banja 1998 is again well met by} 15. h4 $1
Na6 16. h5 $16 {White dominates over the board.}) 12. Bd2 Ne5 13. Be2 Qb6 14.
Kg2 Na6 15. f4 Nd7 {This was Kashlinskaya,A - Drozdova,D Khanty-Mansiysk 2014
Now the simple} 16. Rb1 $146 Nac5 17. Bf3 a5 18. h4 {would have put Black in a
very difficult situation where his pieces desperately lack space and White's
initiative on the kingside develops rapidly.}) 9. h3 Nbd7 (9... exd4 10. Nxd4
Nbd7 ({Inferior is} 10... Qc5 11. Nde2 $1 Qxc4 12. Qxd6 Na6 13. Be3 Ne8 14. Qd2
$16 {Black faced big problems with completing development in Ilincic, Z -
Ivanisevic, I Belgrade 2000}) 11. Re1 {might lead to the same.} (11. Nde2 $5
Ne8 12. Bd2 Ne5 13. b3 {yielded White a stable edge in Gormally, D - Hillarp
Persson, T Guernsey 2001})) ({Usually,} 9... Re8 {does not have independent
value, but it is worth to mention the following interesting line:} 10. Be3 exd4
11. Nxd4 Nbd7 12. Re1 Nb6 ({It is better for Black to play} 12... Ne5 {, and
then} 13. Bf1 {transposes to the main line.}) 13. Qd3 Qa6 14. b3 d5 {This is
the only adequate attempt to release the pressure} 15. exd5 Nbxd5 16. Bd2 Bd7 {
This position occurred in Iljin, S - Bekker Jensen, S Yerevan 1997 Now White
should have played} 17. Na4 $1 b6 18. Nb2 $36 {In this position with a
symmetric pawn structure Black suffers from poor the coordination between his
pieces.}) 10. Re1 ({Less promising is} 10. Be3 exd4 11. Nxd4 Nb6 $1 12. Nb3 Qh5
13. Qxh5 Nxh5 {, and Black is close to reaching equality.}) 10... exd4 ({
The pseudo-aggressive} 10... b5 $6 11. cxb5 cxb5 {runs into} 12. a4 $1 b4 13.
Nb5 Ne8 14. dxe5 Nxe5 (14... dxe5 $2 15. Be3 a6 16. Na7 {White was already
winning in Dizdar,G - Klinova,M New York 1997}) 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Be3 Be6 17.
Qe2 a6 18. Na7 $16 {White is firmly in control.}) ({The attempt to deviate
from releasing the tension in the centre by means of} 10... Re8 11. Be3 Qb4 (
11... exd4 12. Nxd4 {is a transposition.}) {is well met by} 12. d5 $1 cxd5 {
This was Roos,J - Chevaldonnet,F Dijon 1983} ({The pawns are untouchable:} 
12... Qxc4 13. Bf1 Qb4 14. a3 Qa5 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. Qxd6 $16) ({Even worse is} 
12... Qxb2 $2 13. Na4 Qa3 14. Bc1 Qb4 15. Bd2 Qxc4 16. Bf1 $18) {Now White
could have highlighted the drawbacks of the opponent's setup with} 13. Nxd5 $1
Nxd5 14. cxd5 Qxb2 15. Qa4 $36 {with a powerful iniative.}) 11. Nxd4 Ne5 {
The most common and natural continuation. Indeed, attacking the Pc4 is the
main idea of Black's previous play.} (11... Re8 12. Be3 Ne5 ({Too passive is} 
12... a6 $6 13. Qc2 Ne5 14. b3 c5 15. Nde2 Be6 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. Bd2 Qc7 18. f4
Nc6 19. f5 Bc8 20. Bg5 {Black's position was practically lost in Harutyunian,T
- Cori,J Badalona 2015}) (12... Nb6 {is covered in above-mentioned note.}) ({
Dubious is} 12... Qb4 $6 13. Nc2 Qxc4 14. Qxd6 Nb6 15. Rad1 $16) 13. Bf1 {
leads to the same.}) ({Pointless is} 11... Qc5 $6 12. b3 Ne8 13. Be3 {Black
was strategically lost in Smejkal,J - Mrdja,M Baden-Baden 1985}) 12. Bf1 {
This looks somewhat awkward, but White has to cover the Pc4 at the moment.} ({
The merits of Black's setup can be illustrated in the following line:} 12. Qe2
$6 Nfd7 13. Be3 Nb6 14. Nb3 Qb4 {, and Black takes over the initiative.}) 12...
Re8 ({Worth serious attention is} 12... Qb6 $5 {, as recently gained
popularity on the GM level.} 13. Kg2 {I believe, this prophylactic move is the
best reaction to Black's last tricky move.} ({The more natural} 13. Be3 {
runs into} c5 $1 14. Nc2 {This was recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in his book}
({After} 14. Nb3 Be6 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Rae8 17. Kg2 Re7 {Black was fine in
Howell,D - McShane,L London 2017}) {However, it looks like the unbalanced
position that arises by force after} 14... Qxb2 $1 15. Na4 Nf3+ 16. Kh1 Qe5 17.
Qxf3 Qxe4 18. Qxe4 Nxe4 $132 {is very unclear - Black has 2 pawns for the
piece, while White suffers from a lack of harmony, mainly in view of the poor
Na4.}) 13... a6 14. f4 Ned7 {This was Barsov,A - Kamer,K Cesme 2019 Now I
mostly like} 15. Nf3 $146 Qc7 16. e5 Ne8 ({Worse is} 16... dxe5 17. fxe5 Ne8
18. Bf4 Nc5 19. Be3 Ne6 20. Rc1 $36 {[%csl Re8] , and the Ne8 is going to be
stuck for a long time.}) 17. Qe2 dxe5 18. fxe5 f6 19. exf6 Ndxf6 20. Bf4 Qd7
21. Kh2 Nh5 22. Be5 {White retains some pressure due to the better
coordination between his pieces.}) 13. Be3 Be6 {This yields White the bishop
pair, but Black has to connect his rooks as soon as possible.} ({Pointless is} 
13... c5 14. Nb3 Qb4 15. a3 Qb6 16. Nd2 Nc6 17. Rb1 $14 {Black is doomed to
passive defence.}) 14. Nxe6 Rxe6 15. Kg2 $1 {A decent prophylactic move.} ({
Premature is} 15. f4 Ned7 16. Bf2 Nc5 17. Bg2 Rae8 {with a massive pressure on
White's centre.}) 15... Rae8 (15... a6 {can be well met by} 16. c5 $1 dxc5 17.
f4 Rd8 18. Qc2 Ned7 19. Rad1 b5 20. e5 Nd5 21. Bf2 $1 $146 (21. Nxd5 $6 cxd5 {
was unclear in Schachinger, M - Albadri, A Vienna 2010, since the Pd5 is
untouchable.}) 21... Nxc3 22. Qxc3 {White's bishop pair and the pawn majority
on the kingside put Black in danger, even though he is a pawn up.}) ({Hardly
an improvement is} 15... Ned7 16. f3 Nh5 17. Qd2 Be5 18. g4 Nhf6 19. Red1 Nc5
20. Ne2 {Black was doomed to passive defence in Greiner, T - Guevara Pijoan, J
email 2012}) 16. Rb1 $1 {White starts to extend on the queenside.} Ned7 17. f3
{Now White's centre is secured.} a6 ({After} 17... h5 18. b4 Qc7 19. Qd2 Nh7
20. Ne2 $1 $14 {Black struggles to develop any play on the kingside.}) 18. b4
Qc7 19. Rc1 a5 20. a3 axb4 21. axb4 {White was clearly better due to the space
advantage and the bishop pair in Vidit, S - Thipsay, P Aurangabad 2011} *

