h4 17. g4 g5 18. e5 $1 {It Is important to activate the light-squared bishop
before Black can play ..Be5.} Rxe5 19. Rad1 Rb8 20. Re2 Nf8 21. Red2 {The
bishop pair as well as the superior pawn structure offer White excellent
compensation for the pawn.}) ({In case of} 11... h6 12. Rb1 a5 (12... Bd7 {
transposes to 11... Bd7}) {White can benefit from the weakened b5-square with}
13. Ndb5 $1 Bd7 14. Bf4 {Traditionally, the pressure on the c7-pawn is
annoying, so Black's reaction is very natural:} Ne6 15. Bd2 $1 ({But not} 15.
Be3 $6 Ng5 {, and White is forced to give up the dark-squared bishop.}) 15...
Ng5 {This position took place in Gagunashvili,M - Spasov,V Istanbul 2003 Now
White should have played} 16. Kh2 $146 Qc8 (16... Re5 17. h4 Ngh7 18. f3 g5 19.
hxg5 hxg5 20. Be3 $14) 17. h4 Ne6 18. Be3 Qd8 19. Bh3 $14 {Black's
counter-attacking abilities are heavily limited.}) (11... c6 {can often
transpose into other lines, but there is also an independent value:} 12. Qc2 a5
(12... Nfxe4 $6 13. Nxe4 Bxd4 14. Bg5 Qd7 15. Nf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxf6 $40 {leaves
Black's king too exposed.}) ({The tempting} 12... d5 {doesn't seem to work in
view of:} 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. e5 Nfe4 15. Bf4 $1 g5 (15... Bxe5 $2 16. Bxe5 Rxe5
17. f3 $18) 16. Be3 Bxe5 17. Rad1 Nxc3 18. bxc3 $36 {The initiative
overwhlemed Black's extra pawn in Medic, M - Mahini,M Istanbul 2000}) 13. Bf4 {
White is planning to put strong pressure on d6 with 14.Rad1.} Nfd7 {The
satandrd manoevre, that is mainly aimed to lock the h2-b8 diagonal.} ({Hardly
better is} 13... Nh5 14. Be3 a4 15. b4 axb3 16. axb3 Rxa1 17. Rxa1 Be6 ({
Much better was} 17... Qb6 18. Rb1 Qb4 19. Na2 Qa3 20. b4 Ne6 21. Ne2 $14) 18.
b4 Nd7 19. Nxe6 Rxe6 20. Ra7 $16 {White was firmly in control in Vaganian,R -
Jugow,A Frankfurt 1997}) 14. Rad1 Ne5 15. b3 Qb6 16. Be3 a4 17. Rb1 axb3 18.
axb3 Ra3 $6 ({Better is} 18... Ned3 19. Red1 Nb4 20. Qd2 $14) 19. Red1 Qb4 {
We have been following the game Miguel Lago,V - Vidarte Morales,A Mondariz 1995
} (19... Qc7 {can be well met by} 20. Ncb5 $1 cxb5 21. Nxb5 Qa5 22. b4 $18 {
Black's position collapses at once.}) {At this point, White could have
exploited the awkward location of Black's heavy pieces with} 20. Ncb5 $1 cxb5
21. Bd2 $18) 12. Rb1 {A flexible move. White makes b2-b4 more effective and
invites Black to show his cards.} ({The straightforward} 12. b4 Ne6 13. Be3 {
worked well for White in a couple of games, but it seems less effective in
view of} Nxd4 14. Bxd4 c5 $1 15. bxc5 dxc5 16. Bxc5 Rc8 17. Bxa7 Rxc4 {, and
Black has sufficient counterplay.}) 12... a5 ({The somewhat tricky} 12... h6 {
can be well met by the solid} 13. f3 $5 ({The idea of Black's previous move is
based on} 13. b4 Ne6 14. Be3 Ng5 $1 $132 {, and White is not in time to cover
both of his hanging pawns.}) 13... a6 (13... Ne6 14. Nde2 a6 {was seen in
Vachier Lagrave, M - Topalov, V Istanbul 2012 Now I mostly like} 15. a4 $5 $146
a5 16. Be3 b6 17. Qc2 Nc5 18. b3 $14 {yielding c5 for the knight did not solve
Black's strategic problems, and now White can slowly extend.}) 14. Be3 {
The bishop comfortably covers the dark squares around White's king, so f2-f3
was not a very weakening move after all.} Rb8 15. Qd2 {White had a stable
positional advantage in Matlakov, M - Demchenko, A Sochi 2018}) ({The most
popular move is} 12... Qc8 {, but after} 13. Kh2 {Black usually fails to show
the merits of having the queen on c8.} h6 (13... Re5 $6 {is quite common, but
the idea of transferring the rook to h5 is dubious:} 14. f4 Rh5 15. f5 $1 gxf5
16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 {The lack of harmony made Black's position practically
lost in Kantsler, B - Rinberg, A Haifa 2010}) ({The attempt to develop
counterplay on the queenside with} 13... a6 {is not effective in view of} 14.
b4 Ne6 15. Be3 $14 {, and now} c5 $2 16. Nxe6 Bxe6 17. e5 dxe5 18. bxc5 {
led to Black's collapse in Rustemov,A - Shorokhov,A Moscow 2002}) 14. f3 $1 {
Like in above-mentioned note, White's main task is securing the Pe4, so
Black's counter-play would be fully neutralized.} a6 15. Be3 Rb8 16. Qd2 Kh7
17. Nd5 $16 {Black's position was very cramped in Neckar, L - Terreaux, G Sion
1990}) (12... a6 13. b4 Ne6 14. Be3 Rb8 {was seen in a couple of high-level
games.} ({I have also examined} 14... Nxd4 $146 15. Bxd4 Be6 16. c5 $14 {
Black is doomed to passive defence.}) {At this moment I mostly like} 15. Nde2
$5 $146 {, retaining all the pieces on the board, and intending to meet} b5 {
with} 16. c5 $1 {, and Black finds himself in a difficult position. For
instance,} dxc5 17. e5 Nh5 18. g4 {, and the piece is gone.}) 13. b3 {White
consistently prepares b3-b4 and invites Black to show his cards.} h5 (13... h6
{can be traditionally met by} 14. f3 $5 Nh5 ({The following alternatives were
tested and left Black in a very passive position:} 14... a4 15. b4 Ne6 16. Nde2
Ng5 17. h4 Ne6 18. Be3 $16 {Ruck,R - Huber,M Batumi 2018}) (14... Nh7 15. Be3
h5 16. Qd2 Ne6 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Rbd1 $16 {Sviridov,V - Demchenko,A Minsk 2017}
) 15. g4 Nf6 16. Be3 $14 {, heavily limiting Black's counter-attacking
abilities.}) ({As earlier, the artificial} 13... Qc8 14. Kh2 Re5 $6 ({The
attempt to complicate the matters with} 14... h5 15. Bf4 h4 {might backfire:}
16. g4 Ne6 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Nd5 $16 {The Ph4 was very weak in Kuljasevic, D -
Robulj,N Skopje 2018}) 15. f4 Rh5 {is energetically met by} 16. f5 $1 gxf5 17.
Nd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 $16 {Hansen,C - Fressinet,L Oslo 2015}) 14. Bg5 Qc8 15. Kh2
Nh7 16. Be3 c6 ({After} 16... h4 17. g4 Ne6 18. Qd2 Qd8 19. Nxe6 Bxe6 20. f4
$16 {Black was left without any counter-play in Kabatianski,A - Kerek,C
Budapest 1994}) 17. Qd2 Qc7 {This was Ghosh - Solak, Dubai 2014 My new natural
idea at this point is} 18. Rbd1 Rad8 ({Pointless is} 18... h4 19. g4 {,and then
} d5+ 20. Bf4 {leads to material losses.}) 19. Nf3 Be6 20. Bd4 {White's
positional advantage is obvious.} *

