1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4
c6 {By making this move Black covers d5 and opens a pathway for the queen to
b6, so White might have to deal with pressure against the Pd4. In addition,
Black may push d6-d5 in some cases. This position became very popular in the
1940s, when 8...c6 was tested by many of the strongest KID players of that
time, such are Smyslov, Bronstein, and more.} 9. Be3 {This is only White's 7th
most popular choice according to statistics, but a challenging one!} ({The
most common alternatives are} 9. h3) (9. b3) ({and} 9. d5) 9... Ng4 {The most
common response. Black immediately tries to show the drawback of White's
somewhat provocative way of handling the position.} (9... Re8 10. h3 a5 (10...
exd4 11. Nxd4 Nc5 12. Qc2 a5 {leads to a well-known theoretical position that
mostly arises after 8...exd4.}) 11. Qc2 a4 (11... exd4 12. Nxd4 Nc5 13. Rad1
Qe7 14. Rfe1 Nfd7 (14... a4 {is well met by} 15. f4 $1 {, and then} Nfxe4 {
runs into} 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Qxe4 18. Bf2 {Black suffered heavy material
losses in Dautov, R - Akopian, V Tbilisi 1989}) 15. b3 h5 16. f4 Qf8 17. Bf2
$16 {Black desperately lacked space in Bu, X - Chen, F Beijing 2012}) 12. Rad1
Qa5 13. Rfe1 exd4 14. Nxd4 Qb4 15. Bf1 Ne5 ({even worse is} 15... Nc5 $6 16.
Ncb5 Ncxe4 17. Nc7 $18 {Schoeneberg,M - Uhlmann,W Leipzig 1982}) 16. a3 Qa5 17.
f4 Ned7 18. Nf3 Nc5 19. Bf2 Bf8 20. Bd4 {White's positional advantage was
undeniable in Molina, R - Saldano Dayer, H Nova Resende 2009}) 10. Bg5 f6 ({
Even riskier seems} 10... Qb6 11. h3 exd4 {, even though it was tried by a few
strong players, including the great Garry. After} (11... Ngf6 {looks as a
concession:} 12. b3 exd4 13. Nxd4 Nc5 14. Be3 Re8 15. Qc2 a5 16. Rab1 Nfd7 (
16... Qb4 $2 {runs into} 17. Ndb5 $1 cxb5 18. Nxb5 Nfxe4 19. a3 {, and the
queen is gone.}) 17. Rfd1 Qc7 {This was Teterev,V - Gladyszev,O Elets 2014 Now
the natural} 18. Rd2 $146 Nf6 19. Rbd1 Qe7 20. f3 $16 {would have put Black in
a difficult situation with no counterplay.}) 12. Na4 {Black temporarily loses
his knight, but this is not the main issue.} Qa6 13. hxg4 b5 {That's the
point! White's knight is trapped as well.} 14. Be7 Re8 ({After} 14... bxa4 15.
Bxd6 {Black hardly has anything better than} Re8 {with a transposition.}) 15.
Bxd6 bxa4 16. c5 $1 {Despite the material balance, Black finds himself in a
difficult situation - most of his pieces are very passive, while the Pc6 and
the Pd4 are weak.} d3 ({The ''greedy''} 16... Rxe4 {runs into} 17. Ng5 Re5 18.
Nxf7 $1 ({But not} 18. Bxe5 $2 Nxe5 {, and Black takes over the initiative.})
18... Kxf7 19. Qf3+ Kg8 20. Qxc6 {Black's position was ruined in Solak, D -
Mchedlishvili, M Konya 2011}) 17. e5 Nxe5 ({The attempt to complicate the
matters with} 17... a3 $146 {fails to} 18. Re1 $1 axb2 19. Rb1 Qa3 20. Qd2 Nxc5
21. Nd4 Bd7 22. Nxc6 {, and White has a powerful initiative.}) 18. Nxe5 Bxe5
19. Re1 f6 20. Bf1 {Black got under strong pressure in the correspondence game
Wegman, W - Staf, G email 2007}) 11. Bd2 Nh6 ({The more aggressive} 11... f5 {
invites interesting complications, but Black does not seem to be well-prepared
for it} 12. exf5 gxf5 (12... exd4 {is traditionally met by} 13. Bg5 $1 Qb6 14.
Na4 Qa5 15. Nxd4 $16) 13. Ne2 $1 {The knight moves towards f4 in advance and
limits Black's counter-attacking abilities.} Qe8 ({After} 13... e4 14. Nh4 Ndf6
15. f3 exf3 16. Bxf3 Ne4 17. Bf4 $14 {White's chances are preferable due to
the better pawn structure.}) 14. Nh4 Ndf6 {We have been following the game
Lalic, B - Bednar, M Prague 2019} ({The natural} 14... exd4 {is well met by}
15. Bf4 {, and White regains the pawn in a favourable situation:} Nge5 16. Nxd4
Nc5 17. Re1 Qf7 18. Bf1 $14) {My natural improvement at this point is} 15. h3
$146 Nh6 16. Qc2 e4 (16... Qh5 17. Bb4 $16) 17. f3 Qe7 18. Nf4 $16 {White's
pieces are much more harmonious.}) ({Inconsistent is} 11... exd4 12. Nxd4 Nc5
13. h3 Ne5 14. b3 Ne6 15. Be3 $16 {Baranowski,T - Istomin,S email 2011}) 12.
Qc2 {It definitely makes sense to connect the rooks and maintain the tension
